"CORE_NARRATIVE: Traditional frequency-domain methods fail to decouple material reflections from depth cues under low angular resolution (e.g., 9x9), causing networks to blindly learn physical noise. By replacing frequency analysis with a three-layer physical decomposition and geometric feature extraction, we overcome this bottleneck to provide robust material priors. These priors drive a dual-mask routing architecture that explicitly handles non-Lambertian regions, achieving high-precision depth estimation in complex scenes.\n\nINTRO_HOOK: Open by highlighting the fatal flaw in light field depth estimation: non-Lambertian reflections violate Epipolar Plane Image (EPI) linearity, and under low angular resolution (e.g., 9x9 sampling), traditional frequency-domain decoupling completely fails. Emphasize that this failure forces networks to blindly learn noise, fundamentally bottlenecking depth accuracy in complex, real-world scenes.\n\nGAP_BRIDGE: Transition by critiquing existing methods that either rely on high angular resolution for frequency analysis or apply global EPI assumptions that amplify errors on reflective surfaces. Pivot to our core premise: when frequency-domain separation breaks down at 9x9 resolution, we must shift to a geometry-driven physical decomposition to explicitly isolate and route material residuals.\n\nMETHOD_JUSTIFY: Justify the three-layer decomposition and geometric features (like angular gradient) as the direct mathematical remedy to the 9x9 frequency-domain bottleneck, ensuring robust pixel-level material classification via Random Forest. Explain that the GeometricDualMask routing and domain-balanced sampling are strictly motivated by the need to explicitly process these classified non-Lambertian pixels without overfitting to scarce reflective training data.\n\nEXPERIMENT_VALIDATE: Design experiments to explicitly prove the motivation by comparing geometric features against failed frequency-domain baselines at 9x9 resolution, highlighting the Random Forest's 89.6% accuracy and the angular gradient's high discriminative power (Cohen's d = 0.983). Validate the architectural motivation by demonstrating that the dual-mask routing and domain-balanced sampling significantly reduce depth errors specifically in non-Lambertian regions compared to global EPI networks.\n\nCONCLUSION_ECHO: Conclude by reiterating that shifting from frequency-domain to geometry-driven physical decomposition fundamentally resolves the low-resolution material decoupling bottleneck in light field imaging. Highlight that explicitly routing material priors via dual-mask architectures establishes a new, physically grounded paradigm for robust depth estimation in complex reflective scenes."